{% block content %}
	<p>
		On June 12th 2020 I graduated from High School. Of course this was no normal graduation as all of the state laws of social distancing had to be followed. We were required to sign up for a specific time slot with several other families. Although the original plan was to allow these 7-10 families into the building at the same time, this was changed to a single graduation at a time, with stages that each would move through independently. First we walked up to the building where we were met with a short line. Reaching the front, there was large sign reading the numbers 2020, with each number painted separately to match the colors of each of the four local schools. We were given a short time to take pictures, and then moved to the next station, phase, or whatever it should be called. This was another short line behind another family as they put their masks on and entered the building. This area, located under a small tent outside the doors, was where my entire family was required to individually sign a 'wellness form' indicating that nobody currently had symptoms of the Coronavirus. They checked that each of had masks, as they were required inside the building. We waited for a few minutes there, until the family in front of us again moved forward, out of the lobby of the building and onto the next station. Being given the clear from the staff under the tent, we moved past the second hand sanitizer dispenser, and then inside. Just inside the foyer were a few tables where I was given my academic stole and an index card with my name. This is where the process began to really feel like some sort of assembly line, where each step a small piece of the overall graduation was attached. Each of these stations so far were relatively quick and ended with a minute or so of waiting to move on. When the wait was over we were pointed to the next room, and shuffled along. This time it was another picture opportunity. There was a nice screen in the back of the room plastered with my school's logo. Although this was effectively the same space as the room before, with only a single set of permanently open doors between them, here I and my family were allowed to take off our masks while taking the pictures. I enjoyed this one more than the previous ones because the few teachers in the room with us did a really good job of making it feel like some sort of celebrity photo shoot, and the screen behind me only added to it. Taking the various pictures with my family made this station actually take the full time. Once it was over, my family was told to put their masks on, one of the teachers took my index card and we were escorted into the auditorium. My family was pointed to right in front of the stage, with a single isle roped off to direct them where they had to go. I was marched down to the stage and given all of the instructions required for the ceremony, "Stand on the tape, wait for the principle to finish calling you, walk to the table and take a diploma, don't open it, stand in the square in the middle of the stage for pictures, then exit". It was one continuous direction that was fired at me. It almost felt too simple. Was that really going to be my whole graduation? Did I miss something? <br>
		I got to the tape on the floor, about 5 feet from the principal's podium and the teacher escorting my handed him my index card. He read it, looked to me and said congratulations, and shuffled some papers. I quickly asked him before he started if the instructions I was given really were that simple, he said yes, but first I had to look at the camera so the photographer could take some shots. Once the flashes stopped, he started right into his speech. I think the 10 seconds it took for him to read the same lines he must have already read 80+ times were the only seconds of my graduation that each lasted a full second. I could feel my brain questioning if this was really it. It almost seemed silly that I was trying to look professional in front of an audience of 3. I was thinking back to last year, watching my friends graduation, how different their experience was. I would've liked that experience, but here I was, trying to make the most of what the school district could come up with. I heard my name and snapped out of my head. Following the directions as if they were programmed into my, I got my diploma and stood right in the middle of the square. This was the most awkward time because (besides my natural tendency to be awkward) I didn't know if there was anywhere I was supposed to look or how long I should stand there. I'm still not sure if I did it right, but I waited for my family to take their pictures, and then moved on. Walking past the administrators on stage I got a few offhand congratulations before they went back to their conversation. That was a little disappointing over the normal line of handshakes that were given out previous years, but I was actually surprised to see them there given that there are probably over 600 seniors in my town this year. That's a lot of time to stand on stage for each individual's mini ceremony. <br>
		Once I passed them and met back up with my family at the back of the room, the next family started moving in and it was all over. Down a short hallway and out the locked-open front doors. Besides those 10 seconds of speech, it really felt like a blink. Compared to a normal graduation it rightfully could be called a blink considering my that graduation scheduled for 5:00 had completely wrapped up before 5:20. Removing the time taken waiting in line to get into the building it lasted less than a full 10 minutes.
	</p>
